commit.message:
Fix regression by making parsing of `;thread:...` attributes more lenient

Don't require `;thread:...` to be at the first occurrence of `;`; this breaks
`QPassSignals`. Instead, look for it at the end of the command.

Support `QSaveRegisterState` and `QRestoreRegisterState` packets

LLDB uses these to save and restore register states around debuggee function calls.
Use these as cues to start/stop diversions.

We're making some assumptions here about how these are used. We start a diversion
at the first `QSaveRegisterState` and end the diversion when that saved state is
restored. This restores not only the registers on the target thread but all
tracee memory and registers on all threads. During a diversion, register states
can be saved and restored in any order, but restoring a register state after the
diversion has ended won't work.

Add support for debugger-controlled allocation of virtual memory in tracees.

LLDB expects this.

We don't copy these virtual memory areas into tracees. That would get complicated during
time-travel as we save and restore checkpoints. Instead, we store these memory regions
in `GdbServer` and only copy them into tracees when we create a `DiversionSession`,
so that any code executed on behalf of the debugger during the `DiversionSession`
sees the memory regions allocated by the debugger.

This requires us to intercept operations that read and write memory, retargeting them
to the `GdbServer`-managed memory regions if necessary.

One important but subtle issue here is what to do when a `DiversionSession` exits.
LLDB must expect its memory regions to keep their values when a user function call
has completed, since that's what would happen in a normal gdbserver backend. Therefore
during a `DiversionSession` the tracee memory is the source of truth for the contents of
the debugger memory regions. When the session exits normally, we copy the values
back from the tracees to the `GdbServer`'s buffers.

The tricky issue is what to do when a `DiversionSession` exits abnormally because
the user function call crashed or triggered process exit. We want debugging to continue
normally as if nothing bad has happened. For now, we refrain from copying the region
values out of the session in this case. This effectively means the debugger memory region
values revert to their values at the start of the diversion. We'll have to see how
LLDB reacts to that.
Implement 'M' gdbserver command to set memory values with a hexadecimal payload
Remove duplicated handling of DREQ_GET_MEM/DREQ_GET_MEM_BINARY

Skip test transient_fault_replay_all when built with force32bit.

The test uses the `seq` utility, which is most probably 64-bit,
and can therefore not be recorded by a 32-bit rr.

Avoid the half-initialized `GdbServer` state by making `GdbServer::serve_replay` static.

Makes `GdbServer` borrow instead of own the `ReplayTimeline`.

Instead of having `ReplayCommand` stash a pointer to the `GdbServer` for use by the signal handler, have it store the `stop_replaying_to_target` boolean flag directly and point the `GdbServer` at it.

This will make it easier to refactor further so that `ReplayCommand` never needs to see the `GdbServer` object at all.
Create `ExtendedTaskId` to carry aboth a `TaskUid` and a `ThreadGroupUid` and use it instead of `GdbThreadId` where we know we have a specific task that exists.

Fix 32-bit build of RecordTask::try_grow_map.

This got introduced in 7bd2d4ab2.
Always write to `*error` from `PerfCounters::stop()` if `error` is non-null
Remove unused function prototype

Explicitly reject qShlibInfoAddr; it's not documented for Linux, and lldb-server doesn't support it

Intentionally ignore all 'j' related packets for now

Producing JSON output is a bit of a pain so let's just avoid this as long as we can.
Support 'x' packet to read memory in binary format, used by LLDB
Rename some methods to mem_binary
Rename `DREQ_SEARCH_MEM` to `DREQ_SEARCH_MEM_BINARY`

Rename `DREQ_SET_MEM` to `DREQ_SET_MEM_BINARY`

We need to be consistent at naming requests with BINARY because there are both binary and hexadecimal versions of some requests.
Ignore `qStructuredDataPlugins` packets because they're not documented and `lldb-server` doesn't support them
Support `QListThreadsInStopReply` gdbserver packet for LLDB
Avoid passing null pointers to `memcpy`
Use a valid `SupportedArch` for default-initialized `Registers` to avoid undefined behavior
Ensure `TraceWriter::chaos_mode` and `TraceWriter::supports_file_data_cloning_` are properly initialized
Avoid passing an null pointer to `memcpy`
